            <!-- Explanatory content -->
            <section class="prose mt-8">
              <h2>How this chemistry calculator hub works</h2>
              <p>
                This page brings together the most common general‑chemistry
                calculations in one consistent interface. Each tab focuses on a
                core concept, shows the governing equation, and walks you
                through the algebra.
              </p>

              <h3>Moles, mass, and molar mass</h3>
              <p>
                The amount of substance is measured in moles. One mole contains
                Avogadro’s number of particles (\(6.022\times10^{23}\)). The
                basic relationship is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( n = \dfrac{m}{M} \) where \( n \) = moles, \( m \) = mass
                (g), \( M \) = molar mass (g·mol⁻¹).
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, 5.00&nbsp;g of NaCl (M = 58.44&nbsp;g·mol⁻¹)
                contains \( n = 5.00 / 58.44 \approx 0.0856 \) mol.
              </p>

              <h3>Molarity and solution concentration</h3>
              <p>
                Molarity \(M\) is defined as moles of solute per liter of
                solution: \( M = n / V \). The calculator automatically converts
                between mL and L so you can enter volumes in whichever unit is
                convenient.
              </p>

              <h3>Dilution using C₁V₁ = C₂V₂</h3>
              <p>
                When you dilute a solution, the number of moles of solute stays
                the same; only the volume changes. That leads to the dilution
                equation:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( C_1 V_1 = C_2 V_2 \) with all volumes in the same units (L or
                mL).
              </div>
              <p>
                For instance, to make 250&nbsp;mL of 0.10&nbsp;M solution from a
                1.0&nbsp;M stock: \( V_1 = C_2 V_2 / C_1 = 0.10 \times 0.250 /
                1.0 = 0.025 \) L = 25&nbsp;mL.
              </p>

              <h3>Ideal gas calculations</h3>
              <p>
                For many gases at moderate pressures and temperatures, the ideal
                gas law is a good approximation:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( PV = nRT \) where \(R = 0.082057\
                \text{L·atm·mol}^{-1}\text{·K}^{-1}\) (or 8.314&nbsp;J·mol⁻¹·K⁻¹
                in SI units).
              </div>
              <p>
                The tool converts kPa to atm and °C to K internally so you can
                mix practical lab units with the theoretical equation.
              </p>

              <h3>pH, pOH, and acidity</h3>
              <p>For strong monoprotic acids and bases, you can approximate:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                \( \text{pH} = -\log_{10} [\text{H}^+] \) \( \text{pOH} =
                -\log_{10} [\text{OH}^-] \) \( \text{pH} + \text{pOH} = 14 \) at
                25&nbsp;°C.
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator lets you go in any direction: from concentration
                to pH, from pH to concentration, or from hydroxide to hydrogen
                ion via water’s ion product.
              </p>

              <h3>Stoichiometry with mole ratios</h3>
              <p>
                Once you have a balanced chemical equation, the coefficients
                give you mole ratios between reactants and products. If the
                equation is \( aA \rightarrow bB \), then:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">\( n_B = n_A \dfrac{b}{a} \)</div>
              <p>
                This is the backbone of yield calculations, limiting‑reagent
                problems, and many lab preparations.
              </p>

              <h2>Safety and good practice</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Always wear appropriate PPE (gloves, goggles, lab coat) when
                  handling chemicals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Double‑check units and significant figures before using
                  results in real experiments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Follow your institution’s lab manual and local regulations for
                  storage and disposal.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

